CSS box model
CSS box model is used to create a rectangular box that contains margins, borders, padding, and content. There are two types of CSS box model:

1. Strict Box Model: In this model, the width and height of the content box does not include the padding and border width of the box. The total width and height of the box is the sum of the width and height of the content box plus the padding, border and margin width.
```css
.example {
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  padding: 10px;
  border: 5px solid black;
  margin: 10px;
}
```
In the above example, the total width of the box will be 200px + 20px (padding) + 10px (margin) + 10px (margin) = 240px. And the total height of the box will be 200px + 20px (padding) + 10px (margin) + 10px (margin) = 240px.

1. Loose Box Model: In this model, the width and height of the content box includes the padding and border width of the box. The total width and height of the box is the sum of the width and height of the content box plus the margin width.
```css
.example {
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  padding: 10px;
  border: 5px solid black;
  margin: 10px;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
```
In the above example, the total width of the box will be 200px. And the total height of the box will be 200px.

How can I do responsive website with css
Responsive design is a technique used to design a website that adapts to different screen sizes and devices. Here are some ways to create a responsive website with CSS:

1. Use Media Queries: Media queries allow you to apply different styles to different devices and screen sizes. You can define different styles based on screen width, orientation, resolution, and other factors.
```css
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  /* Styles for screens smaller than 768px */
}

@media screen and (min-width: 768px) and (max-width: 1024px) {
  /* Styles for screens between 768px and 1024px */
}

@media screen and (min-width: 1024px) {
  /* Styles for screens larger than 1024px */
}
```
1. Use Flexible Grids: Using flexible grids like flexbox and CSS Grid can make your layout more responsive. By using percentage values for width and height, your layout will adapt to different screen sizes and devices.
```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  justify-content: space-between;
}

.item {
  width: 25%;
  height: 200px;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
}

@media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  .item {
    width: 50%;
  }
}

@media screen and (max-width: 500px) {
  .item {
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```
1. Use Responsive Images: Images can take up a lot of space on a webpage, especially on smaller screens. You can use the srcset attribute to load different sizes of images based on the screen size.
```html
<img src="small.jpg" srcset="small.jpg 320w, medium.jpg 640w, large.jpg 1024w" alt="example image">
```
1. Use Mobile First Design: Start by designing for mobile devices and then add styles for larger screens. This will ensure that your website is optimized for the smallest screen size first, and then you can add more styles as the screen size increases.

By using these techniques, you can create a responsive website that looks great on all devices and screen sizes.

