Building a web app from scratch using Node.js is an exciting project. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you get started:

1. Install Node.js: Before diving into the development, download and install the latest stable version of Node.js from the official website (https://nodejs.org/en/download/). This will provide you with the necessary tools to run JavaScript on the server-side.

2. Set up your development environment: Choose your preferred code editor or IDE. Popular options include Visual Studio Code, Atom, or Sublime Text. Install any necessary plugins or extensions to enhance your coding experience.

3. Understand the basics of Node.js: Familiarize yourself with core concepts such as modules, events, streams, and non-blocking I/O. Spend some time going through the official Node.js documentation (https://nodejs.org/en/docs/) and tutorials available online.

4. Learn about package management: Node.js uses npm (Node Package Manager) for managing dependencies. Learn how to install, update, and remove packages using npm. Check out the npm documentation (https://docs.npmjs.com/) for more information.

5. Set up a project structure: Start by creating a new folder for your project and navigate to it using the command line. Initialize a new npm project by running `npm init` and following the prompts. This will create a `package.json` file to manage your project's dependencies and metadata.

6. Create a simple server: In your project folder, create a new file called `server.js`. This file will contain the code for your server. Use the `http` module to create a server and handle incoming requests. Here's a basic example:

```javascript
const http = require('http');

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  res.statusCode = 200;
  res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');
  res.end('Hello, World!\n');
});

server.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server running on port 3000');
});
```

7. Test your server: Save the `server.js` file and run `node server.js` in your command line. Open your browser and navigate to `http://localhost:3000`. You should see the text "Hello, World!" displayed in your browser.

8. Implement routes: To handle different URLs, you'll need to create route handlers. Update your `server.js` file to handle multiple routes:

```javascript
const http = require('http');

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  if (req.url === '/') {
    res.statusCode = 200;
    res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');
    res.end('Hello, World!\n');
  } else if (req.url === '/about') {
    res.statusCode = 200;
    res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');
    res.end('About us!\n');
  } else {
    res.statusCode = 404;
    res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');
    res.end('404 - Not Found\n');
  }
});

server.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server running on port 3000');
});
```

9. Study web frameworks: Node.js has various web frameworks that simplify the development process. Some popular options include Express.js, Koa.js, and Sails.js. Choose one of these frameworks and follow their documentation to create more robust web applications.

10. Leverage external modules: To enhance your web app's functionality, you can use external modules available on npm. Some useful modules include `body-parser` for handling form data, `dotenv` for managing environment variables, and `jade` or `ejs` for templating.

As you progress, continue learning about web development concepts like databases, authentication, and API integrations. Practice by building simple projects, and gradually take on more complex challenges.

