You have a 3-gallon jar and a 5-gallon jar, both empty. You need to measure exactly 4 gallons of water using these jars.
Fill the 3-gallon jar first, then pour it into the 5-gallon jar. Fill the 3-gallon jar again and pour it into the 5-gallon jar until the 5-gallon jar is full, which will leave 1 gallon in the 3-gallon jar. Empty the 5-gallon jar and pour the 1 gallon from the 3-gallon jar into the 5-gallon jar. Fill the 3-gallon jar again and pour the entire contents into the 5-gallon jar, which will hold 4 gallons of water.

Here is some Java code to represent the solution:

```java
public class WaterJarPuzzle {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] jars = new int[]{0, 0}; // initialize the jars to 0 gallons

        // Fill the 3-gallon jar
        jars[0] = 3;

        // Pour the 3-gallon jar into the 5-gallon jar
        jars[1] = jars[0];

        // Fill the 3-gallon jar again
        jars[0] = 3;

        // Pour the 3-gallon jar into the 5-gallon jar until full
        jars[1] = 5;

        // Leave 1 gallon in the 3-gallon jar
        jars[0] = 1;

        // Empty the 5-gallon jar
        jars[1] = 0;

        // Pour the 1 gallon from the 3-gallon jar into the 5-gallon jar
        jars[1] = 1;

        // Fill the 3-gallon jar again
        jars[0] = 3;

        // Pour the entire contents of the 3-gallon jar into the 5-gallon jar
        jars[1] = 4;

        // Print the result
        System.out.println("The 5-gallon jar now contains exactly 4 gallons of water.");
    }
}
```

Here is a Python function that checks whether a given integer is prime or not:

```python
def is_prime(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return False
    elif n <= 3:
        return True
    elif n % 2 == 0 or n % 3 == 0:
        return False
    i = 5
    while i * i <= n:
        if n % i == 0 or n % (i + 2) == 0:
            return False
        i += 6
    return True
```

This function first checks whether the input `n` is less than or equal to 1, because prime numbers are greater than 1. Then, it checks whether `n` is 2 or 3, because these numbers are prime. Afterwards, it checks whether `n` is divisible by 2 or 3, as no other prime number can be divisible by either.

From here, it checks all other numbers up to the square root of `n` to see if it is divisible by any of them. We only need to check numbers of the form `6k ± 1` as all other numbers are divisible by 2 or 3.

This algorithm is efficient and improves upon the simple loop from 2 to `n`. It reduces the number of potential divisors to check from `n-1` to `sqrt(n)`, significantly reducing the time to check larger numbers.

If `n` is divisible by any number from 2 to its square root, then it is not prime. If `n` is not divisible by any number from 2 to its square root, then it is prime.

